\subsection{The SIR Model}

The Susceptible–Infected–Recovered (SIR) model describes the spread of infectious disease within a closed population. The total population, $N$ is divided into three groups:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $S(t)$: susceptible individuals,
    \item $I(t)$: infected individuals,
    \item $R(t)$: recovered individuals.
\end{itemize}
The governing equations are
\begin{align}
\frac{dS}{dt} &= -\beta S I, \\
\frac{dI}{dt} &= \beta S I - \gamma I, \\
\frac{dR}{dt} &= \gamma I,
\end{align}
where $\beta$ is the transmission rate and $\gamma$ is the recovery rate.
The term $\beta S I$ ariises from the assumption that the rate of infection is proportional to both the number of susceptible and infected individuals, reflecting random interactions within the population. The recovery term on the other hand, $\gamma I$, assumes that infected individuals recover at a constant rate.

